Omg I am SO sick and tired of people saying that Rey was "insanely powerful without training" lol sure, she hadn't discovered her latent Force abilities until after meeting BB-8, but she DID learn how to survive all by herself on the desolate and dangerous desert planet of Jakku!

J.J. even shows her holding her own in a Fight against like three or four of Unkar Plutt's henchmen who tried stealing BB-8 away from her.

I thought they made it perfectly clear that she was NO helpless "damsel in distress" or pushover early on in The Force Awakens. She knew her way around Imperial starships and their technology because she had spent her life scavenging parts from fallen wreckage all over the surface of the planet. And, that's why she was both a good pilot and mechanic, as well.

All established pretty effectively by Abrams in her character's introduction. (I thought.) And, as for her seemingly sudden Force abilities, she clearly has a very natural strength within herself that just happened to have been realized at a point in time in which she was encountering another Force user, Kylo Ren.

Who undoubtedly helped her figure out for herself that whatever this new "thing" she was discovering within herself was, she could see him using, even on her.

Anyway, Rey has never seemed "too overpowered" to me. Because of the circumstances she was clearly shown to have come from, and environment she'd been raised.

ANYONE would have had to become fairly tough and self-sufficient to survive as long and as well as she did.

Because now it does make more sense and power the phrase they have made so beaten today with which I say goodbye.

snippet.textDisplay:
Pretty positive JJ and Rian have a clause that states they can’t say they weren’t on the same page at all. Iger and Kennedy should’ve let Treverrow execute his vision, whatever it was.

Months from now I hope JJ and Rian both admit they were trying to subvert each other. While I enjoyed TFA, I felt it was a bit of a rehash with new and compelling characters and ideas, but TLJ straight up challenged convention and turned the entire franchise and what we think of heroes on their ears. Rian made bold decisions, with the exception of one (I am not fond of the Canto Bight sequence either), and regardless of whether it was to serve the purposes of his proposed new trilogy or the mere fact it was a creative visionary trying to push the boundaries of what we know SW to be, bringing JJ back was a mistake.

Also, why announce the Emperor in the trailers and the crawl?! Even if he was to be the big bad, that could’ve been an “oh shit” moment that got flushed. Major faux pas. Also, JJ/Terrio should’ve had enough faith in Kylo as a character to be the primary villain post-Snoke. Also would’ve made his redemption all the better.

There were a lot of great things and the film was beautiful, funny, and enjoyable, but also so many things they could’ve done differently, and this just felt like the path of least resistance (no pun intended). Kinda’ wish they’d have taken one more year to crack that story and released it in 2020.
